SIMPLE: overrun
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overrun
<hw>O`ver*run"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Overran</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Overrun</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Overrunning</conjf>. ]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To run over; to
grow or spread over in excess; to invade and occupy; to take possession
of; <as>as, the vine <ex>overran</ex> its trellis; the farm is
<ex>overrun</ex> with witch grass.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those barbarous nations that <qex>overran</qex> the world.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To exceed in distance or speed of running; to go
beyond or pass in running.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ahimaaz ran by the way of the plain, and <qex>overran</qex>
Cushi.</q> <rj><qau>2 Sam. xviii. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To go beyond; to extend in part beyond; <as>as, one
line <ex>overruns</ex> another in length</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In machinery, a sliding piece is said to
<xex>overrun</xex> its bearing when its forward end goes beyond
it.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To abuse or oppress, as if by treading
upon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>None of them the feeble <qex>overran</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To carry over, or
back, as type, from one line or page into the next after, or next
before.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To extend the contents of (a line,
column, or page) into the next line, column, or page.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overrun</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Overrun
<hw>O`ver*run"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To run, pass,
spread, or flow over or by something; to be beyond, or in
excess.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Despised and trodden down of all that <qex>overran</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>To extend beyond its due or
desired length; <as>as, a line, or advertisement,
<ex>overruns</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overrunner</ent>⟦br⟧
